\section{${ }^{19}$ F Magic Angle Spinning NMR Spectroscopy and Density Functional Theory Calculations of Fluorosubstituted Tryptophans: Integrating Experiment and Theory for Accurate Determination of Chemical Shift Tensors}


\begin{abstract}
The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift is a sensitive NMR probe of structure and electronic environment in organic and biological molecules. In this report we examine chemical shift parameters of $4 \mathrm{~F}-$, 5F-, 6F-, and 7F-substituted crystalline tryptophan by magic angle spinning (MAS) solid-state NMR spectroscopy and density functional theory (DFT). Significant narrowing of the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ lines was observed under fast MAS conditions, at spinning frequencies above $50 \mathrm{kHz}$. The parameters characterizing the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift tensor are sensitive to the position of the fluorine in the aromatic ring and, to a lesser extent, the chirality of the molecule. Accurate calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ magnetic shielding tensors require the PBE0 functional with a $50 \%$ admixture of a Hartree-Fock exchange term, as well as taking account of the local crystal symmetry. The methodology developed will be beneficial for ${ }^{19}$ F-based MAS NMR structural analysis of proteins and protein assemblies.
\end{abstract}

