\section{INTRODUCTION}
Fluorine, or specifically, the magnetically active ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ isotope, is an excellent NMR probe for applications in biological and biochemical studies due to its favorable magnetic and chemical properties. Being a $100 \%$ naturally abundant spin- $1 / 2$ nucleus with a very high gyromagnetic ratio (third after ${ }^{3} \mathrm{H}$ and ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ ), it possesses $83 \%$ sensitivity compared to ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$. Fluorine chemical shifts are exquisitely sensitive to changes in local environment, because its magnetic shielding is dominated by a large paramagnetic term: the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift range is over $300 \mathrm{ppm}$, 30-fold larger than that of ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H} .{ }^{1-2}$ Fluorine is absent from virtually all naturally occurring biomolecules, small or large. In addition, fluorine can easily be biosynthetically incorporated into proteins in the context of either natural or unnatural amino acids or attached as a fluorinated tag to reactive amino acids, such as cysteine. ${ }^{1-5}$ In particular, tryptophan residues are often chosen for fluorine incorporation because of their relative sparseness in most proteins. ${ }^{6-7}$ Biosynthetic incorporation into proteins and peptides using standard $E$. coli expression systems is easy, ${ }^{3,} 8-10$ and the effects on conformation or biological activity of proteins upon fluorination are small, in most cases. ${ }^{3}$

Indeed, ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ has found interesting applications in NMR spectroscopy of biologically significant materials already. ${ }^{1-5,10-12}$ In solution, ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ has been used as a probe to investigate protein folding, ${ }^{4}$ ligand binding, ${ }^{10}$ and conformational dynamics, ${ }^{2}$ including exciting applications to membrane proteins, such as $G$ protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs). ${ }^{13-14}$ In the solid state, ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift probes have been applied to membrane-associated peptides and proteins, using oriented samples and static experiments, as well as MAS NMR spectroscopy. ${ }^{15-21}$

One limitation that prevents the widespread use of fluorine as a NMR reporter in biochemical applications is the lack of a systematic understanding of the relationship between ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts and local environments. This knowledge gap exists because there are, at present, no robust protocols for quantum mechanical calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts. Such calculations have been traditionally difficult, ${ }^{22-23}$ due to the stringent requirements on the inclusion of electron-correlation terms, given the large number of electrons and free electron pairs in fluorine. Although earlier studies have suggested that Hartree-Fock self-consistent-field (HF SCF) or post-Hartree-Fock calculations are essential to compute accurate ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts, ${ }^{22,}{ }^{24}$ recent reports suggest that density functional theory (DFT) can be used, provided that explicit solvent models are employed ${ }^{25}$ and appropriate hybrid functionals with sufficient exact exchange terms are applied. ${ }^{26-27}$ These developments are very promising.

Another challenge specific to ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ solid-state NMR spectroscopy arises from its generic broad lines, ${ }^{21}$ often limiting fluorine-based correlation experiments when multiple sites are present. Currently the literature on ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ magic angle spinning (MAS) NMR in biological systems is sparse, predominantly reporting on MAS studies at spinning frequencies below $25 \mathrm{kHz}$, although a recent study demonstrated resolution enhancements for sitagliptin at 35 $\mathrm{kHz}^{28}$ Developing optimal experimental conditions necessary for the acquisition of highquality datasets still need to be established.

To develop a robust protocol for ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectroscopy-based characterization of structure and dynamics in fluorinated solids, it is imperative to examine a sufficiently large number of model systems to benchmark ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR's use for biological applications. In this report, we present a combined ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR and DFT study of fluorosubstituted tryptophans (Figure 1). We assess the dependence of the experimental ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift tensor (CST) parameters on the fluorine position in the aromatic ring and the chirality of the tryptophan molecule. For 5F-L-Trp, 5F-L-Trp $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, and 6F-DL-Trp, whose crystal structures we solved, DFT calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ CST were carried out. Good agreement between experiment and theory was obtained when the PBE0 functional with a $50 \%$ admixture of Hartree-Fock exchange terms was employed. On the experimental side, the use of high MAS frequencies of over $50 \mathrm{kHz}$ is essential to obtain sufficiently narrow lines. Overall, the integrated approach presented here should set the stage for a wide variety of applications in organic and biological systems.

\section{MATERIALS AND METHODS}
\section{Fluorosubstituted tryptophans}
4F-DL-tryptophan, 5F-L-tryptophan, 6F-L-tryptophan were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich. 5F-DL-tryptophan was purchased from MP Biomedicals, LLC (Santa Ana, CA). 6F-DLtryprophan was purchased from Apollo Scientific Ltd (UK). 7F-DL-tryptophan was purchased from Amatec Chemical Co. Ltd (Hong Kong). For measurements of the powders, all fluorosubstituted tryptophans were used without further purification.

\section{Crystallization of fluorosubstituted tryptophans and crystal structure determination}
5F-L-tryptophan, 5F-DL-tryptophan, and 6F-DL-tryptophan were recrystallized from a $30 \%$ water/ethanol mixture. Crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained at ambient temperature. The details of the crystal structure determination are provided in the Supporting Information.

\section{${ }^{19}$ F MAS NMR experiments}
${ }^{19}$ F MAS NMR experiments on 4F-DL-tryptophan, 5F-DL-tryptophan, 5F-L-tryptophan, 6F-DL-tryptophan, 6F-L-tryptophan, and 7F-DL-tryptophan were carried out at room temperature $\left(21^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right.$ ) on a $9.4 \mathrm{~T}$ NMR spectrometer comprised of a wide-bore Magnex Scientific magnet and a Bruker AVANCE console. The spectrometer was equipped with a $3.2 \mathrm{~mm}$ Varian T3 MAS HXY probe. The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ Larmor frequency was $376.476 \mathrm{MHz}$. The samples comprised 20 mg of either 4F-DL-tryptophan, 5F-DL-tryptophan, 6F-DLtryptophan, or 6F-L-tryptophan packed in a 3.2-mm Varian rotor. For 5F-L-tryptophan and 7F-DL-tryptophan, $10 \mathrm{mg}$ and $4 \mathrm{mg}$ of sample, were packed into rotors, respectively. ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra were collected at MAS frequencies of $5 \mathrm{kHz}, 7 \mathrm{kHz}, 9 \mathrm{kHz}$, and $11 \mathrm{kHz}$, controlled to within $\pm 10 \mathrm{~Hz}$ by a Tecmag MAS controller. The typical ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F} 90^{\circ}$ pulse length was $1.4 \mu$ s. During the odd-numbered transients, a $180^{\circ}$ pulse was applied before the $90^{\circ}$ excitation pulse to suppress ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ background signals. The recycle delay was $10 \mathrm{~s}$.

${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR experiments on $3.0 \mathrm{mg}$ of 5F-DL-tryptophan, $3.0 \mathrm{mg}$ of 5F-L-tryptophan, $1.8 \mathrm{mg}$ of 6F-DL-tryptophan, and $2.2 \mathrm{mg}$ of 6F-L-tryptophan, respectively, were also carried out on a Varian $14.1 \mathrm{~T}$ narrow bore magnet equipped with a Bruker AVIII HD spectrometer operating at $564.278 \mathrm{MHz}$ and outfitted with a $1.3 \mathrm{~mm}$ Bruker HCN MAS probe. ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra were collected at MAS frequencies of $8 \mathrm{kHz}, 11 \mathrm{kHz}$ (except for 5F-DLtryptophan), $20 \mathrm{kHz}, 30 \mathrm{kHz}, 35 \mathrm{kHz}, 40 \mathrm{kHz}, 50 \mathrm{kHz}$, and $60 \mathrm{kHz}$; the frequencies were controlled to within $\pm 5 \mathrm{~Hz}$ by a Bruker MAS controller. The actual sample temperature was calibrated using $\mathrm{KBr}$ as a temperature sensor and was maintained at $22 \pm 1{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ throughout the experiments using a Bruker temperature controller. The typical ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F} 90^{\circ}$ pulse length was $1.3$ $\mu \mathrm{s}$. The recycle delay was $3 \mathrm{~s}$.

The effects of magnetic field strength and ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ decoupling were assessed using ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR experiments with 5F-DL-tryptophan. MAS NMR experiments were carried out on an 11.7 T wide-bore Bruker AVANCE III spectrometer outfitted with a $2.5 \mathrm{~mm}$ MAS HFX probe. Larmor frequencies were $500.1 \mathrm{MHz}\left({ }^{1} \mathrm{H}\right)$ and $470.6 \mathrm{MHz}\left({ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}\right) .8 \mathrm{mg}$ of 5F-DLtryptophan were packed into a $2.5 \mathrm{~mm}$ thick-walled Bruker rotor. ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra were collected at MAS frequencies of $5 \mathrm{kHz}, 7 \mathrm{kHz}, 11.111 \mathrm{kHz}$, and $30 \mathrm{kHz}$, with the frequencies controlled to within $\pm 5 \mathrm{~Hz}$ by a Bruker MAS controller. The actual sample temperature was calibrated using $\mathrm{KBr}$ as a temperature sensor and was maintained at $20 \pm 1^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ throughout the experiments using a Bruker temperature controller. The typical $90^{\circ}$ pulse lengths were $2.5 \mu \mathrm{s}\left({ }^{1} \mathrm{H}\right)$, and $2.5 \mu \mathrm{s}\left({ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}\right)$. Single-pulse ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ spectra were acquired by using a small-angle excitation pulse with a pulse length of $0.5 \mu \mathrm{s} .{ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ TPPM decoupling ${ }^{29}$ (91 $\mathrm{kHz}$ ) was used during the acquisition period. The recycle delay was $3 \mathrm{~s}$.

MAS NMR experiments were also carried out on a $19.96$ T Bruker AVANCE III spectrometer operating at $800.095 \mathrm{MHz}$, outfitted with a $1.9 \mathrm{~mm}$ MAS HX probe and a $1.6$ mm MAS HFDXY Phoenix probe. $9 \mathrm{mg}$ of 5F-DL-tryptophan were packed into a $1.9 \mathrm{~mm}$ thin-wall Bruker rotor. ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra were collected at MAS frequencies of 11 $\mathrm{kHz}, 15 \mathrm{kHz}, 30 \mathrm{kHz}$, and $40 \mathrm{kHz}$, and the frequencies were controlled to within $\pm 5 \mathrm{~Hz}$ by a Bruker MAS controller. The actual sample temperature was calibrated using $\mathrm{KBr}$ as a temperature sensor and was maintained at $25 \pm 1{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ throughout the experiments using a Bruker temperature controller. The typical $90^{\circ}$ pulse length for ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ was $1.8 \mu \mathrm{s}$. During the odd-numbered transients, a $180^{\circ}$ pulse was applied before the $90^{\circ}$ excitation pulse to suppress ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ background signals. The recycle delay was $3 \mathrm{~s}$.

$7.6 \mathrm{mg}$ of 5F-DL-tryptophan were also packed into a $1.6 \mathrm{~mm}$ Varian rotor. ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra were collected at a MAS frequency of $40 \mathrm{kHz}$, regulated to within $\pm 5 \mathrm{~Hz}$ by a Bruker MAS controller. The typical $90^{\circ}$ pulse lengths were $2.7 \mu \mathrm{s}\left({ }^{1} \mathrm{H}\right)$, and $2.7 \mu \mathrm{s}\left({ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}\right) .{ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ TPPM decoupling $(10 \mathrm{kHz})$ was used during the acquisition period. The recycle delay was $80 \mathrm{~s}$.

${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts were referenced to trifluoroacetic acid, TFA (100 $\mu \mathrm{M}$ solution in $25 \mathrm{mM}$ sodium phosphate buffer, $\mathrm{pH}$ 6.5), using an external reference ( $0 \mathrm{ppm})$. All ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS spectra were processed using TopSpin. Baseline correction was employed using manually defined baseline points.

\section{Determination of chemical shift tensors}
The principal components of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift tensors were determined by fitting the spinning sideband intensities according to the Herzfeld-Berger protocol. ${ }^{30}$ The peak intensities were obtained from TopSpin and were input into the HBA program, version 1.7.5. ${ }^{31}$

\section{DFT calculations}
${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ magnetic shielding tensor calculations were carried out on 5F-L-TrpH $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, 5F-DL-Trp (L-form), and 6F-DL-Trp. For each, molecular clusters comprised of four molecules were generated from the crystal structures with GaussView, the graphical interface in Gaussian09 32 (Figure 4A-C).

All-atom geometry optimizations were carried out in Gaussian09, using the B3LYP functional and 6-31 $\mathrm{G}$ basis set. The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ magnetic shielding tensor calculations were performed with the Amsterdam Density Functional Theory suite of programs ${ }^{33}$ (ADF2017), using a hybrid PBE0 functional with 50\% Hartree-Fock (HF) exchange, and a TZ2P allelectron basis set (no frozen core). The numerical quality was set to 'very good' for each calculation using Becke integration. Magnetic shielding tensors were calculated only for the central fluorine atoms.

The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts were referenced by converting absolute magnetic shieldings $\mathrm{s}$ into chemical shifts, using the relation $\delta_{\mathrm{i}}=\sigma_{\mathrm{ref}}-\sigma_{\mathrm{i}}$, with the value of $\sigma_{\text {ref }}$ determined by linear regression between calculated and experimental shifts. ${ }^{34}$

\section{SIMPSON and SIMMOL calculations}
Calculations were performed for recrystallized 5F-L-Trp $\cdot \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, 5F-DL-Trp (L-form), and 6FDL-tryptophan. One fluorine in the crystal structure was chosen as the central atom and all other neighboring fluorines within $6 \AA$ radius were considered for calculating dipolar coupling tensors. The SIMMOL program 35 reads in the atomic coordinates of the selected fluorines in the PDB format, from which it generates dipolar couplings and Euler angles.

The spectra of the crystals were simulated in SIMPSON. ${ }^{36}$ The experimental CSA tensors (Table 1) at $14.1 \mathrm{~T}\left({ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}\right.$ Larmor frequency of $\left.564.278 \mathrm{MHz}\right)$ and a MAS frequency of 11 $\mathrm{kHz}$ were used, with and without the F-F couplings added from the X-ray structures.

The peak intensities of the simulated spectra were obtained using NMRDRAW. ${ }^{37}$ These intensities and the isotropic chemical shifts (Table 1) were used in Herzfeld-Berger analysis for extracting the principal components of the tensors, the reduced anisotropy and the asymmetry parameter.

\section{RESULTS}
\section{${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra of fluorosubstituted tryptophans}
${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectra of powder and crystalline tryptophan with fluorine substitutions in the 4-, 5-, 6-, and 7-positions of the indole ring were acquired at magnetic field strengths of 9.4, 14.1, and $19.96 \mathrm{~T}$, and at MAS frequencies ranging from 5 to $60 \mathrm{kHz}$ (Figure 2, and S1S2 of the Supporting Information). Increasing the MAS frequency from 20 to $60 \mathrm{kHz}$, in the absence of proton decoupling, results in dramatic line narrowing and increases in peak intensity, due to improved efficiency of the rotational averaging of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift anisotropy (CSA) and ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}^{19} \mathrm{~F} /{ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}-{ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ dipolar interactions (Figure 2; Table S1 of the Supporting Information). As can easily be appreciated from the comparison provided in Figure 2B, the spectral resolution attained for 5F-DL-tryptophan at $14.1 \mathrm{~T}$ and a MAS frequency of $60 \mathrm{kHz}$ in the absence of decoupling is similar to that observed in experiments at $19.96 \mathrm{~T}$ and a MAS frequency of $40 \mathrm{kHz}$, in the presence of ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ decoupling. At $60 \mathrm{kHz}$, the linewidths are $~ 1 ~ p p m$ for all samples under investigation, indicating that the nonrecrystallized tryptophan powders are crystalline. This was confirmed by X-ray powder diffraction of 4F-DL-, 5F-DL-, 6F-L-, and 6F-DL- tryptophans (Figure S3 of the Supporting Information).

The above findings are important: they demonstrate that ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR spectroscopy can be widely applied, even in the absence of specialized probes that are capable of ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ decoupling while detecting ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$.

\section{Experimental chemical shift tensors of fluorosubstituted tryptophans}
To determine accurate ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift parameters of the different fluorosubstituted tryptophans, we acquired ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS spectra at different magnetic field strengths $(9.4,14.1$, and $19.96 \mathrm{~T})$ and at MAS frequencies ranging between 5 and $60 \mathrm{kHz} .{ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ isotropic shifts are summarized in Table 1 . The MAS isotropic shifts of $4 \mathrm{~F}-\operatorname{Trp}$ and $6 \mathrm{~F}$-Trp are similar to the solution NMR values, to within $1 \mathrm{ppm}$, for fluorosubstituted L-Trp molecules. ${ }^{5}$ For 7F-LTrp, a difference of $3.1 \mathrm{ppm}$ is observed (the solution NMR shift is $-58.8 \mathrm{ppm}$ ). Isotropic shifts range from $-41.4$ to $-59.6 \mathrm{ppm}$, influenced by the position of the fluorine in the indole ring and the local environments. Interestingly, MAS isotropic shifts appear to be sensitive to the hydration state of the molecule, as seen for 5F-Trp (Figure 2C). The shift of $-46.4 \mathrm{ppm}$ appears to be associated with the monohydrate form of the 5F-L-Trp. The chemical shift of -48.7 ppm was observed in microcrystalline non-hydrated powders of 5F-DL-Trp (minor peak), 5F-L-Trp (major peak), and is the only species in the recrystallized 5F-DL-Trp. Interestingly, a pure L-enantiomer was detected in the single-crystal X-ray diffraction experiments. The L-conformation was assigned based on the handedness that gave values of the Flack parameter closest to zero, albeit the standard error values were high (see Supporting Information). The major resonance in the 5F-DL-Trp powder ( $-47.7 \mathrm{ppm})$ is assigned to the D-enantiomer by exclusion.

Representative spectra acquired at MAS frequencies ranging between 5 and $15 \mathrm{kHz}$ are provided in Figure 3 (all spectra are shown in Figures S1-S2 of the Supporting Information). ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ CSTs have been previously determined for 5F-L, 5F-DL-, 6F-L- and 6F-DL-tryptophan, and the reported values for the reduced anisotropy parameter, $\delta_{\sigma}$, for 5F-DL-Trp differ by $2.2 \mathrm{ppm}$ for the MAS $^{38}$ vs. the single-crystal static ${ }^{39}$ NMR study. These differences may be due to experimental uncertainties or, more likely, different crystal forms. In the present work, we recorded multiple MAS spectra for each compound, which permitted us to extract accurate CST parameters and assess the range of experimental errors in these measurements.

Experimental CST parameters were obtained by analyzing the spinning sideband intensities using the Herzfeld-Berger protocol. ${ }^{30}$ All values are summarized in Table 1 . The reduced anisotropy parameters range between $48.6$ and $67.6 \mathrm{ppm}$. The positioning of the fluorine in the indole ring exerts the largest effect on the shift, and smaller, but distinct, differences $(0.5$ - $3.2 \mathrm{ppm}$ ) are observed for molecules of different chirality. All of the tensors are rhombic, with the asymmetry parameters ranging from 0.44-0.50 (for 5F-Trp) to $0.95$ (for 4F-Trp). Overall, pronounced differences in the CST parameters are observed, underscoring the remarkably high sensitivity of fluorine chemical shift tensors to local electronic structure.

CST parameters for every fluorosubstituted tryptophan and each set of spectra (Table S2 of the Supporting Information) permitted us to evaluate the experimental errors carefully. The experimental uncertainties in the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ reduced anisotropy parameter $\delta_{\sigma}$, extracted from the spinning sideband analyses of the MAS spectra, are of the order of 0.8-3.7 ppm, or 5-7\% of the total magnitude of $\delta_{\sigma}$. This error range is reasonable, since accurate values rely on the intensities of the outer, low-intensity sidebands, whose quantification becomes more difficult for slower MAS frequencies. We also considered the effect of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}-{ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ homonuclear couplings on the spinning sideband intensities for the 5F-DL-Trp, 5F-L-Trp $\cdot \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, and $6 \mathrm{~F}$ DL-Trp crystalline samples whose structures we solved (Table 2). For 5F-DL-Trp and 5F-LTrp $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, the effects are negligible. For 6F-DL-Trp the effects were small, but discernable, in the absence of ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ decoupling, and need to be considered when CST parameters are extracted from the spectra. Overall, the CSTs for 5F-L/DL and 6F-L/DL tryptophan determined here are in good agreement with the published values, ${ }^{38,40}$ within experimental uncertainty.

Density functional theory calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift tensors of fluorosubstituted tryptophans

Recent studies indicate that in the DFT calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shifts in solids, using the Amsterdam Density Functional (ADF) program with the PBE0 functional, ${ }^{41}$ a $50 \%$ HartreeFock (HF) exchange admixture term, and an all-electron Slater-type (TZ2P) basis set yields values in reasonable agreement with experiment, if the molecular clusters reflect the overall symmetry of the crystal lattice. ${ }^{26-27}$ As revealed by the XRD patterns (Figure S3 of the Supporting Information), the crystal forms of the powdered fluorosubstituted tryptophans are not the same as the reported X-ray structures of the parent L-tryptophan, ${ }^{42}$ DL-tryptophan ${ }^{43}$ or $5 F$-DL-tryptophan ${ }^{39}$ in the Cambridge crystallographic data base. We therefore restricted our chemical shift calculations to $5 \mathrm{~F}-\mathrm{L}-\mathrm{Trp}$, 5F-L-Trp $\cdot \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, and 6F-DLTrp crystals, whose structures we solved.

Four molecule clusters were constructed, using the crystal coordinates. The molecular geometries of these clusters are shown in Figure 4(A-C), and the results of the chemical shift calculations are summarized in Figure $4 \mathrm{D}$ and Table 1. Gratifyingly, the calculated tensors are in reasonable overall agreement with the experimental values with a slope of $1.12$ for the correlation between experimental and calculated chemical shift tensor components. Given that we restricted our calculations to the $5 \mathrm{~F}$ - and $6 \mathrm{~F}$-substituted tryptophans for which crystal structures were solved, the chemical shift range is too small (5.8 and $6.9 \mathrm{ppm}$ for the isotropic shift and reduced anisotropy, respectively) to conduct rigorous analyses with respect to the quality of the calculations. Nevertheless, the slope of $1.12$ for the principal components of the CST in the four-molecule clusters suggests that these models do not fully capture the long-range electrostatic effects on the magnetic shielding. This is in line with previous studies, ${ }^{26-27}$ and a result of the fact that fluorine magnetic shieldings are dominated by long-range electrostatic contributions. Future studies will be conducted on larger molecular cluster models (15-17 molecules; 400-500 atoms) and on 4F- and 7F-substituted crystalline tryptophans of known structures.

It should also be noted, that periodic structure calculations do not yield better agreement with experiment, and large cluster calculations using appropriately constructed symmetryadapted molecular clusters and high level of theory appear to be necessary, as we have demonstrated previously for fluorine in a wide variety of environments. ${ }^{27}$

\section{DISCUSSION}
Solid state ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ NMR chemical shift parameters were determined for a series of crystalline tryptophans containing fluorine at the 4-, 5-, 6-, and 7- positions. The isotropic and anisotropic components of the CSTs in these molecules are very sensitive to the positioning of the fluorine atom in the indole ring, thereby making fluorotryptophans excellent ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ NMR probes in protein studies, as has been previously shown for solution NMR studies. ${ }^{5,} 10$ One important result of the current work is the demonstration that the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ lines are narrow at a MAS frequency of $60 \mathrm{kHz}$, diminishing the need for ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ decoupling. This observation holds true for proteins as well, making ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR investigations on a broad range of large biological molecules and assemblies practical and accessible to many laboratories. Although we currently do not have access to ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ 'ultrafast' MAS probes (frequencies of $100-110 \mathrm{kHz}$ ), it is possible to extrapolate our findings to MAS frequencies above $100 \mathrm{kHz}$, where, similar to the ${ }^{1} \mathrm{H}$ ultrafast MAS NMR studies of organic molecules and proteins, ${ }^{44-45}$ further line narrowing and sensitivity gains are expected.

In addition to our experimental studies by MAS NMR spectroscopy, we also performed DFT calculations of chemical shift tensors in fluorosubstituted tryptophan crystals with known structures. This investigation was prompted by the paucity of literature on quantum chemical calculations of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ NMR parameters, both for organic and biological systems. Our findings demonstrate that density functional theory can be used successfully for the calculation of ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ CSA parameters, provided a high percentage (50\%) of the HF exchange term is used in the functional and the wavefunction is expanded in a basis of Slater-type atomic orbitals. Future investigations for improving the accuracy of these calculations will focus on large molecular clusters that reflect the overall crystal symmetry and capture long-range electrostatic effects.

\section{CONCLUSIONS}
Our integrated experimental ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ MAS NMR and computational DFT study of fluorosubstituted tryptophans permitted a thorough evaluation of the influence of the local environment on the ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ chemical shift tensor and demonstrated the advantages of fast-MAS (60 $\mathrm{kHz}$ or greater) experiments for studying ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$-containing solid biological materials. The approach presented here is broadly applicable for characterization of other organic solids by ${ }^{19}$ F MAS NMR spectroscopy and holds particular promise for studies employing fluorosubstituted tryptophans in proteins and protein assemblies.

